// =============================================================================
// core.math.frameworks — trusted-axiom packages for external mathematical frameworks
// =============================================================================
//
// This module postulates key results from external formal-mathematics
// frameworks as @framework-tagged axioms. Every axiom carries an explicit
// citation so `verum audit --framework-axioms` can enumerate the trusted
// boundary of any proof that depends on them.
//
// ARCHITECTURE: meta-classifier-relative coordinates.
//
// Of the packaged frameworks below, `diakrisis` is the L5+ canonical-
// primitive meta-classifier — it defines the coordinate system (ν, τ, ε)
// in which the other frameworks live. Concretely:
//
//   • `diakrisis` declares the 5 foundational axioms (relative consistency,
//     articulation/enactment Morita duality, dual no-go, dual gauge kernel,
//     dual-primitive initiality) that establish the (Fw, ν, τ) coordinate
//     space.
//
//   • All OTHER frameworks (`lurie_htt`, `schreiber_dcct`, `connes_*`, etc.)
//     are *named coordinate points* within that space — each carries a
//     specific (ν, τ) location read by `core.theory_interop.coord` and
//     `verum audit --coord`. The framework itself is rigorous in its own
//     standard literature; its *position relative to all others* is
//     governed by the meta-classifier.
//
// In other words: when you write `@framework(lurie_htt, "HTT 5.2.7")` you
// are simultaneously saying "this axiom postulates HTT 5.2.7" AND "this
// axiom lives at coordinate (ν=ω, τ=intensional) in the meta-classifier
// system shipped by `core.math.frameworks.diakrisis`". The two readings
// coexist because Diakrisis is meta-classifier-neutral about *which*
// theorems hold inside each framework — it only fixes the ordering.
//
// The seven packaged frameworks are:
//
//   lurie_htt               — Lurie, "Higher Topos Theory" (2009).
//                             Presentability, ∞-topos formation, adjoint
//                             functor theorem in the ∞-categorical setting,
//                             accessible categories, Kan extensions.
//
//   schreiber_dcct          — Schreiber, "Differential cohomology in a
//                             cohesive ∞-topos" (arXiv:1310.7930).
//                             Cohesive modalities, super-cohesion,
//                             rheonomy, the differential-cohesive hexagon.
//
//   connes_reconstruction   — Connes–Chamseddine (2008). Spectral
//                             reconstruction of smooth Riemannian manifolds
//                             from real spectral triples.
//
//   petz_classification     — Petz, "Monotone metrics on matrix spaces"
//                             (1996). Classification of quantum Fisher
//                             information metrics by operator-monotone
//                             functions.
//
//   arnold_catastrophe      — Arnold–Mather, catastrophe normal forms
//                             for codimension ≤ 4 (A_k, D_k, E_6/7/8).
//
//   baez_dolan              — Gordon–Power–Street (1995) / Baez–Dolan
//                             coherence for tricategories and higher
//                             n-category theories.
//
//   diakrisis               — Canonical-primitive metaclassification
//                             package: relative-consistency under 2
//                             inaccessibles, articulation/enactment
//                             Morita duality (M ⊣ A biadjunction),
//                             dual no-go for absolute practice, dual
//                             gauge-surjection kernel, dual-primitive
//                             initiality.
//
// Every use of one of these axioms in downstream code surfaces as an
// entry in `verum audit --framework-axioms`. The kernel's AxiomRegistry
// stores each axiom's FrameworkId (framework, citation), and any
// .verum-cert export carries the dependency list along.
//
// See docs/verification/framework-axioms for the full story.

public mount core.math.frameworks.lurie_htt;
public mount core.math.frameworks.schreiber_dcct;
public mount core.math.frameworks.connes_reconstruction;
public mount core.math.frameworks.petz_classification;
public mount core.math.frameworks.arnold_catastrophe;
public mount core.math.frameworks.baez_dolan;
public mount core.math.frameworks.owl2_fs;

// Meta-classifier package (L5+ canonical-primitive metaclassification)
// — defines the (Framework, ν, τ) coordinate space of VUVA §10.4 in
// which the six coordinate-point frameworks above live. See
// `core.math.frameworks.diakrisis` for the five foundational axioms
// and VUVA §10.4.1 for the architectural relationship.
public mount core.math.frameworks.diakrisis;

// Meta-classifier extension packages — carry further structural
// theorems atop the canonical-primitive five. Each axiom name is
// foundation-neutral; framework annotation cites the corpus theorem
// for trusted-boundary audit.
public mount core.math.frameworks.diakrisis_biadjunction;
public mount core.math.frameworks.diakrisis_stack_model;
public mount core.math.frameworks.diakrisis_extensions;
public mount core.math.frameworks.diakrisis_acts;

// Weak-stratum coordinate-point frameworks — bounded-arithmetic systems
// (V_0 / V_1 / S^1_2 / V_NP / V_PH / IΔ_0) at the ν^weak ∈ [0, ω-1]
// stratum. Each has ν^weak < ω (strictly below the full-arithmetic
// stratum); the discrete jump at the weak/full boundary is the
// content of Theorem 137.T. Used by VFE-8 @verify(complexity_typed)
// strategy for polynomial-time verification of bounded-arithmetic
// programs.
public mount core.math.frameworks.bounded_arithmetic;

// VFE §18.7 — foundation-marketplace runtime registry. Self-describing
// catalogue of every framework with its (Fw, ν, τ) coordinate +
// classification tier (Standard / VerifiedExtension / Experimental).
// Exposes registry_meta_classifier_unique invariant (per VUVA §10.4.1)
// + sample population for the canonical Standard six-pack + meta-
// classifier + bounded-arithmetic family. CLI wiring (`verum
// frameworks list / show / validate`) is V1 work.
public mount core.math.frameworks.registry;
